The dataset is about the houses found in a given California district and some summary stats about them based on the 1990 census data.

Setup

library(INLA)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loading required package: sp
## This is INLA_24.06.27 built 2024-06-27 02:47:30 UTC.
##  - See www.r-inla.org/contact-us for how to get help.
##  - List available models/likelihoods/etc with inla.list.models()
##  - Use inla.doc(<NAME>) to access documentation
housing<-read.csv("housing.csv")
#removing rows with NA's, there are only a few of these
housing=housing[complete.cases(housing), ]
#creating a new covariate
housing$average_bed_rooms=housing$total_bedrooms/housing$households
head(housing)

The covariates available from the data are as follows:

  • longitude
  • latitude
  • housing_median_age (median age of houses in district)
  • total_rooms (total rooms in all houses in district)
  • total_bedrooms (total bedrooms in all houses in district)
  • population (population of district)
  • households (number of households in district)
  • median_income (median income in district)
  • median_house_value (median house value in district)
  • ocean_proximity (categorical covariate about proximity of district to ocean)
  • average_bed_rooms (average number of bedrooms of houses in district).
# We split the original dataset into two parts, training and test
housing.training<-housing[seq(from=1,to=nrow(housing),by=2), ]
housing.test<-housing[seq(from=2,to=nrow(housing),by=2), ]

set.seed(1)
# sample <- sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), nrow(iris), replace=TRUE, prob=c(0.7,0.3))
# housing.training <- housing[sample, ]
# housing.test <- housing[!sample, ]
# Create a function conducting data preprocessing
preprocess_data <- function(data) {
# Log transformation of median housing value
data$log_med_housing_value <- log(data$median_house_value)
  
# Scaling numerical features
data$longitude.scaled <- scale(data$longitude)
data$latitude.scaled <- scale(data$latitude)
data$housing_median_age.scaled <- scale(data$housing_median_age)
data$log_med_inc.scaled <- scale(log(data$median_income))
data$avg_bedrooms.scaled <- scale(data$average_bed_rooms)
  
# Generate polynomial features
data$median_age_scaled_2 <- scale((data$housing_median_age)^2)
data$median_age_scaled_3 <- scale((data$housing_median_age)^3)
data$median_age_scaled_4 <- scale((data$housing_median_age)^4)
data$log_med_inc.scaled_2 <- scale((log(data$median_income))^2)
data$log_med_inc.scaled_3 <- scale((log(data$median_income))^3)
data$log_med_inc.scaled_4 <- scale((log(data$median_income))^4)
  
# Generate the interaction housing_median_age*log(median_income),
data$int_med_age_log_med_inc <- scale(data$housing_median_age*(log(data$median_income)))

# One-hot encoding for ocean proximity
ocean_prox_df <- as.data.frame(model.matrix(~ ocean_proximity - 1, data = data))
names(ocean_prox_df) <- c("ocean_prox_less1H", "ocean_prox_inland", "ocean_prox_island", "ocean_prox_near_bay", "ocean_prox_near_ocean")
data <- cbind(data, ocean_prox_df)
  
return(data)
}

# Call the function on your dataset
housing.training <- preprocess_data(housing.training)

Simple Bayesian Linear Regression

We try to fit a Bayesian Linear regression model in INLA (with Gaussian likelihood) using the housing.training dataset such that the response variable is the log(median_house_value) and the covariates in the model are:

  • longitude
  • latitude
  • housing_median_age
  • log(median_income)
  • ocean_proximity
  • average_bed_rooms.

We used scaled versions of all non-categorical covariates to ensure numerical stability (limiting the range of covariates ensures all covariates are comparable on the same scale) and interpretability of our priors.

# Fitting the Bayesian Linear Regression 
# Utilize uninformative priors
prior.beta <- list(mean.intercept = 0, prec.intercept = 1/100, mean = 0, prec = 1/100)

# Fit the model
m1 <- inla(formula = log_med_housing_value ~ longitude.scaled+latitude.scaled+housing_median_age.scaled+log_med_inc.scaled+ocean_proximity+avg_bedrooms.scaled, family="gaussian", data=housing.training, control.fixed = prior.beta, control.predictor = list(compute = TRUE), control.compute = list(dic=T,cpo=T,waic=T, config=TRUE))

Random effects

Lets improve the model above by including a random walk 1 (rw1) random effect model for the housing_median_age, and an autoregressive 1 (ar1) random effect model for log(median_income).

# Utilize uninformative priors
prior.beta <- list(mean.intercept = 0, prec.intercept = 1/100, mean = 0, prec = 1/100)

# Fit the model with rw1 and ar1 effect
# Do we need to add housing_median_age.scaled on top of it being a rw1?
m2 <- inla(formula = log_med_housing_value ~ longitude.scaled+latitude.scaled+f(housing_median_age.scaled, model="rw1")+f(log_med_inc.scaled, model="ar1")+ocean_proximity+avg_bedrooms.scaled, family="gaussian", data=housing.training, control.fixed=prior.beta,control.predictor = list(compute = TRUE), control.compute = list(dic=T,cpo=T,waic=T, config=TRUE))

Spatial Random Effects for Location

Let us improve our model by using a spatial random effects model for the location by creating a Bayesian regression model in inlabru with Gaussian likelihood. The fixed effects in the model are as follows using scaled versions of non-categorical covariates:

  • longitude
  • latitude
  • housing_median_age
  • \((housing\_median\_age)^2\)
  • \((housing\_median\_age)^3\)
  • \((housing\_median\_age)^4\)
  • log(median_income)
  • \((\log(median\_income))^2\)
  • \((\log(median\_income))^3\)
  • \((\log(median\_income))^4\)
  • housing_median_age*log(median_income)
  • ocean_proximity
  • average_bed_rooms

We can include a spatial random effect by creating a spde2 random effect for the location (longitude, latitude), with Matern covariance.

library(inlabru)
## Loading required package: fmesher
library(sf)
## Linking to GEOS 3.11.0, GDAL 3.5.3, PROJ 9.1.0; sf_use_s2() is TRUE
library(splancs)
## 
## Spatial Point Pattern Analysis Code in S-Plus
##  
##  Version 2 - Spatial and Space-Time analysis
library(gridExtra)
library(lattice)

# Define the spatial area as a matrix
area <- as.matrix(housing.training[,c("longitude", "latitude")]) 
plot(area)

# Create the prediction domain by defining boundaries around the spatial data points. We use the parameters convex and concave to control how the boundary is fit around our data points (coordinates)

# convex (larger/smaller value results in a smoother/rougher boundary)
# concave (larger value allows the boundary to cut into areas with fewer points, making it more flexible, a high value would result in boundaries that are entirely separate from each other)
# Allow convex and concave to be negative to follow the data distribution more precisely  
prdomain <- inla.nonconvex.hull(area,
  convex = -0.03, concave = -0.05,
  resolution = c(100, 100))

# Create the mesh over the domain. Max.edge specifies the maximum edge lengths for the triangles (the first argument 0.45 specifies the lengths for the inner extension and the second for the outer), influencing mesh resolution and smoothness. Cutoff avoids building too many triangles at regions with lots of data points 
loc.mesh <- inla.mesh.2d(boundary = prdomain, max.edge = c(0.45, 1), cutoff = 0.2)

# Create dataframe containing the locations
Locations = data.frame(easting=housing.training$longitude, northing=housing.training$latitude) 

# Matern correlation, defining the prior distributions for the range rho and the standard deviation sigma. 
# the argument for range states that there is a 50% probability that the range is larger than or equal to 1 unit of the spatial data (e.g., 1km)
# the argument for sigma states that there is a 10% probability that the strength of the spatial random effect (spatial variability) is greater than or equal to 12 
loc.spde = inla.spde2.pcmatern(mesh = loc.mesh,
           prior.range = c(1, 0.5), 
           prior.sigma = c(12, 0.1)) 

# Convert the locations dataframe into a sf object by assigning spatial geometry to each data point
housing.training$geometry <- sf::st_as_sf(Locations, coords = c("easting", "northing"))$geometry

# Specify the formula with ocean_prox_near_ocean as reference category
cmp <- log_med_housing_value ~ floc(geometry, model = loc.spde) + longitude.scaled + latitude.scaled + housing_median_age.scaled + median_age_scaled_2 + median_age_scaled_3 + median_age_scaled_4 + log_med_inc.scaled + log_med_inc.scaled_2 + log_med_inc.scaled_3 + log_med_inc.scaled_4 + int_med_age_log_med_inc + ocean_prox_inland + ocean_prox_island + ocean_prox_near_bay + ocean_prox_near_ocean + avg_bedrooms.scaled + Intercept(1)

# samplers=prdomain and domain arguments restrict the model to the spatial domain and the mesh 
m3.bru <- bru(cmp, data=housing.training, family="gaussian", samplers=prdomain,
              domain = list(coordinates = loc.mesh),

# Sensitivity checks and using a finer mesh
# Create the area
area <- as.matrix(housing.training[,c("longitude", "latitude")]) 
plot(area)

prdomain <- inla.nonconvex.hull(area,
  convex = -0.03, concave = -0.05,
  resolution = c(100, 100))

# Create a finer mesh
loc.mesh.sens <- inla.mesh.2d(boundary = prdomain, max.edge = c(0.1, 1), cutoff = 0.2)

# Create dataframe containing the locations
Locations = data.frame(easting=housing.training$longitude, northing=housing.training$latitude) 

# Matern correlation adjusting the prior to have a higher degree of uncertainty
loc.spde.sens = inla.spde2.pcmatern(mesh = loc.mesh.sens,
           prior.range = c(1, 0.5), 
           prior.sigma = c(200, 0.1)) 

housing.training$geometry <- sf::st_as_sf(Locations, coords = c("easting", "northing"))$geometry

# Specify the formula with ocean_prox_near_ocean as reference category
cmp.sens <- log_med_housing_value ~ floc(geometry, model = loc.spde.sens) + longitude.scaled + latitude.scaled + housing_median_age.scaled + median_age_scaled_2 + median_age_scaled_3 + median_age_scaled_4 + log_med_inc.scaled + log_med_inc.scaled_2 + log_med_inc.scaled_3 + log_med_inc.scaled_4 + int_med_age_log_med_inc + ocean_prox_inland + ocean_prox_island + ocean_prox_near_bay + ocean_prox_near_ocean + avg_bedrooms.scaled + Intercept(1)

Model Comparison

We compare all our models based on the goodness of fit measures

Model Comparison
Model DIC NLSCPO WAIC
Model 1 7001.285 3512.786 7031.834
Model 2 6338.976 3178.43 6357.986
Model 3 2010.756 1017.021 1988.165

We can see that as we increase the complexity of our model, by incorporating random effects (with a rw1 and ar1 random effects) and then by incorporating polynomial terms, interaction terms and spatial random effects (through the SPDE), all performance metrics improve. Overall, INLA Model 3 have much better performance than the simple Bayesian linear regression model, INLA Model 1 and the Bayesian model with random effects, INLA model 2.

Predictive Performance

We will now evaluate the predictive performance of these models by performing two tests for all 3 models.

In the first test, we compute the posterior mean of the log(median_house_value) for the districts in the training dataset housing.training. Compute the median absolute difference between the posterior means of the log(median_house_value) and its true values on the training dataset. This can be done by including the posterior means in an array \(v\) , the true values in an array \(t\), and computing \(\text{median}(|v-t|)\).

In the second test, we will evaluate the log(median_house_value) ’s posterior predictive means on the test dataset housing.test. Compute the median absolute difference between the log(median_house_value) ’s posterior predictive mean and its true value on the test dataset.

housing.test$geometry <- sf::st_as_sf(Locations.test, coords = c("easting", "northing"))$geometry

# Specify the formula with ocean_prox_near_ocean as reference category
cmp <- log_med_housing_value ~ floc(geometry, model = loc.spde.test) + longitude.scaled + latitude.scaled + housing_median_age.scaled + median_age_scaled_2 + median_age_scaled_3 + median_age_scaled_4 + log_med_inc.scaled + log_med_inc.scaled_2 + log_med_inc.scaled_3 + log_med_inc.scaled_4 + int_med_age_log_med_inc + ocean_prox_inland + ocean_prox_island + ocean_prox_near_bay + ocean_prox_near_ocean + avg_bedrooms.scaled + Intercept(1)

m3.bru.test <- bru(cmp, data=housing.test, family="gaussian", samplers=prdomain.test, domain = list(coordinates = loc.mesh.test), options=list(control.inla=list(tolerance=1e-10), control.compute=list(cpo=T,dic=T,waic=T)))

# Evaluate the posterior predictive mean on the test dataset
m3_diff_test <- median(abs(m3.bru.test$summary.fitted.values$mean[1:length(housing.test$log_med_housing_value)] - housing.test$log_med_housing_value))

cat("Performance of the posterior mean in model 3 of the log median house value against the test dataset:", m3_diff_test)
## Performance of the posterior mean in model 3 of the log median house value against the test dataset: 0.147881

As we can see, model 3 with the spatial random effects had the lowest prediction error when evaluating the median absolute difference between the posterior predictive mean against the true housing value. Furthermore, we can see that the difference between the performance of model 1 and model 2 is very small, suggesting that including rw1 and ar1 random effects did not result in a significant improvement in the accuracy of the model. The significant outperformance of model 3 compared to models 1 and 2 is expected as the SPDE is able to capture/account for location specific effects on the response (log housing value) which would therefore, produce more accurate predictions.

Posterior Predictive Checks

It is essential that we perform posterior predictive checks (using replicates) on all 3 models fitted on the housing.training dataset to ensure our models accurately reflect the characteristics of our data.

# Create a function to generate replicate data and plot the test functions
require(fBasics)
## Loading required package: fBasics
posterior_samples <- function(model) {

nsamp <- 3000
n <- nrow(housing.training)
housing.samples <- inla.posterior.sample(n=nsamp, result=model)
    
yrep <- matrix(0,nrow=n,ncol=nsamp)
y <- housing.training$log_med_housing_value
predictor.samples <- inla.posterior.sample.eval(function(...) {Predictor},
housing.samples)

sigma.samples <- 1/sqrt(inla.posterior.sample.eval(function(...) {theta},
housing.samples))

yrep <- matrix(0,nrow=n,ncol=nsamp)

for(row.num in 1:n){
yrep[row.num, ]<- predictor.samples[row.num, ]+rnorm(n=nsamp,mean=0,sd=sigma.samples)
}

yrepmin <- apply(yrep,2,min)
yrepmax <- apply(yrep,2,max)
yrepmedian <- apply(yrep,2,median)
yrepskewness <- apply(yrep,2,skewness)
yrepkurtosis <- apply(yrep,2,kurtosis)

par(mfrow = c(3, 2))  # Set up multiple plots

#Predictive checks using replicated data - minimum
hist(yrepmin,col="gray40", main = "Minimum Values", xlab = "Values", xlim=c(min(yrepmin, min(y)), max(yrepmin, min(y))))
abline(v=min(y),col="red",lwd=2)

#Predictive checks using replicated data - maximum
hist(yrepmax,col="gray40", main = "Maximum Values", xlab = "Values", xlim=c(min(yrepmax, max(y)), max(yrepmax, max(y))))
abline(v=max(y),col="red",lwd=2)

#Predictive checks using replicated data - median
hist(yrepmedian,col="gray40", main = "Median Values", xlab = "Values", xlim=c(min(yrepmedian, median(y)), max(yrepmedian, median(y))))
abline(v=median(y),col="red",lwd=2)

#Predictive checks using replicated data - skewness
hist(yrepskewness,col="gray40", main = "Skewness Values", xlab = "Values", xlim=c(min(yrepskewness, skewness(y)), max(yrepskewness, skewness(y))))
abline(v=skewness(y),col="red",lwd=2)

#Predictive checks using replicated data - kurtosis
hist(yrepkurtosis,col="gray40", main = "Kurtosis Values", xlab = "Values", xlim=c(min(yrepkurtosis, kurtosis(y)), max(yrepkurtosis, kurtosis(y))))
abline(v=kurtosis(y),col="red",lwd=2)
}

Does the test function applied on our observed data fall within the test functions applied to the posterior predicted replicates
*The test function of the observed data falls on the edge of the range
Model Minimum Maximum Median Skewness Kurtosis
Model 1 Yes No Yes Yes No
Model 2 Yes Yes* Yes No Yes
Model 3 Yes No Yes No No

The minimum, maximum, median, skewness and kurtosis were used as test functions because it allows us to compare the similarity of the distribution of the observed data with the distribution of the predicted data. To determine the accuracy of samples from the posterior, the histogram plots of the posterior samples (with the vertical red line indicating the test function of the observed data) should be centered around the vertical line. The table above summarises how similar the distribution of the posterior predictive replicates is to the observed data. It shows that model 2 performs the best out of all the models, although, the posterior replicates still show considerable deviance for all test functions except the median. Furthermore, model 3 tends to perform worse in terms similarity as the range of the posterior predictive replicates are very narrow. This suggests that the models for predicting housing value are not reflective of the observed data in terms of the distributional properties (such as skewness, median, kurtosis, etc), and can be improved.
